The novel features of the invention are set forth with particularity in the appended claims. The invention itself, however, both as to organization and methods of operation, together with further objects and advantages thereof, may best be understood by reference to the following description, taken in conjunction with the accompanying drawings in which:


FIG. 1 is a front elevational view of the surgical device of the present invention;


FIG. 2 is an isometric view of the implement of the surgical device;


FIG. 3 is an exploded isometric view illustrating the details of the implement of the surgical device;


FIG. 4 is an exploded isometric view of the tissue clip of the implement of the surgical device;


FIG. 5 is an isometric view of the tissue clip of the implement of the surgical device placed into a target blood vessel;


FIG. 6 is a side elevational view in section of the tissue clip and the target blood vessel depicted in FIG. 5;


FIG. 7 is an exploded isometric view of the frame of the implement of the surgical device;


FIG. 8 is an isometric view of the frame depicted in FIG. 7 being placed together with the tissue clip and blood vessel depicted in FIG. 5, also showing a partial view of the cassette inserted into the frame;


FIG. 9 is an isometric sectional view of the frame and cassette placed together with the tissue clip and blood vessel;


FIG. 10 is an isometric view of the implement of the surgical device, with a sectional view of the cassette, and showing the tissue clip inserted into a graft blood vessel;


FIG. 11 is an isometric sectional view of the implement of the surgical device with the target and graft blood vessels held together in the end-to-side manner;


FIG. 12 is an exploded isometric view of the cassette, illustrating the details of the components;


FIG. 13 is an isometric view of the internal portion of the cassette shown in their initial alignment (before firing);


FIG. 14 is a top view of the internal portion of the cassette depicted in FIG. 13 showing the initial location of the two surgical, spiral needles;


FIG. 15 is an isometric view of the implement of the surgical device holding together the target and graft blood vessels after the cassette has been completely pushed into the frame;


FIG. 16 is an isometric view of the implement depicted in FIG. 15, with part of the implement removed for clarity, showing more clearly the formation of a passageway between the target and graft blood vessels;


FIG. 17 is a sectional view of the distal portion and blood vessels taken along line 17--17 of FIG. 15;


FIG. 18 is an isometric view of the rollers of the implement being rotated by flexible shafts in order to advance the two spiral needles;


FIG. 19 is an isometric view of the implement, with a part of it removed for clarity, after the suture filaments have been placed into the target and graft blood vessels by the advancement of the spiral needles;


FIG. 20 is a perspective view of the implement of the surgical device depicting the removal of an end cover from the cassette;


FIG. 21 is an isometric view of the implement depicting the removal of the anastomosed blood vessels from the distal portion;


FIG. 22 is a front elevational view of the handle of the surgical device with a portion cutaway to view the internal components;


FIG. 23 is a proximal end elevational view of the handle of the surgical device, with a part cutaway to view the internal components;


FIG. 24 is an isometric view of an alternate embodiment of the tissue clip shown in FIG. 3; and


FIG. 25 is a sectional view of the alternate embodiment of the tissue clip inside a target blood vessel such as the coronary artery.


The drawings are not necessarily to scale.
